html.body: Synthesis of catecholamines from dietary tyrosine to dopamine, norepinephrine and epinephrine is crucial for brain development. Dopamine primarily functions in the central nervous system as a modifier of fine movement (eg. Parkinsons disease occurs when dopamine is lacking primarily in late life), or in brain reward pathways (eg. schizophrenia occurs when dopamine is too abundant, primarily early in life). Epinephrine (adrenalin) and norepinephrine (noradrenalin) are the primary peripheral and central, respectively, vasoconstrictors. These hormones are involved in the fight or flight response in all vertebrates, and excessive levels of epinephrine have been found in animals in pack leader positions (alpha males).Website=http://www.beatcfsandfms.org/html/neurotransmitters.htmlWebsite=http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/entrez/query.fcgi?cmd=Retrieve&db=pubmed&dopt=Abstract&list_uids=1105716Website=http://www.neuro.wustl.edu/neuromuscular/lab/catechol.htm#comtWebsite=http://www.nobel.se/medicine/laureates/1970/axelrod-lecture.pdfWebsite=http://www.pharmacology2000.com/lectures/Autonomics/Introduction/page4.htm
